# Animation Contract

This file defines rules for UI motion, transitions, and animation behavior.

It does NOT define:
- architecture rules (see boundaries.mdc)
- UI structure (see ui-boundaries.mdc)
- state behavior (see reactivity-runtime.mdc)
- hooks composition (see hooks.mdc)

---

# 1. Core Principle

Animations must support UX clarity, not decorative intent.

Rule:
- motion must improve understanding of state changes

---

# 2. Motion Purpose Discipline

Allowed purposes:
- state transition feedback
- spatial continuity
- hierarchy clarification
- interaction feedback

Forbidden:
- purely decorative motion without functional value
- motion that obscures UI state
- motion that delays user interaction unnecessarily

Rule:
- every animation must have a UX justification

---

# 3. Performance First

Rules:
- prefer transform and opacity animations
- avoid layout-triggering animations (reflow-heavy)
- avoid animating layout properties (height, width, top, left) when possible
- keep animations GPU-friendly

Rule:
- animations must not degrade runtime performance

---

# 4. Duration and Timing Consistency

Rules:
- use consistent timing scale across the system
- avoid arbitrary animation durations
- prefer standardized easing curves

Rule:
- motion system must feel cohesive across features

---

# 5. Reduced Motion Support

Rules:
- respect user preference for reduced motion
- disable or simplify animations when reduced motion is enabled
- ensure no loss of functionality when animations are removed

Rule:
- accessibility overrides animation behavior

---

# 6. State Transition Animation

Rules:
- animations must reflect state transitions, not control them
- avoid coupling animation timing with business logic
- animation should never block state updates

Rule:
- state drives animation, not the inverse

---

# 7. Component-Level Responsibility

Rules:
- components own their own animations
- shared animation patterns must be abstracted only when reused
- avoid global animation side-effects

Rule:
- animations are local unless proven reusable

---

# 8. Layout Stability

Rules:
- avoid layout shift during animations
- preserve content stability during transitions
- avoid jarring positional changes unless intentional

Rule:
- UI must remain structurally stable during motion

---

# 9. Animation Composition

Rules:
- prefer simple animations over chained complex motion
- avoid cascading animation dependencies
- avoid multiple competing animations on same element

Rule:
- motion complexity must remain controlled and readable

---

# 10. Anti-Patterns

Forbidden:

- layout thrashing animations
- uncontrolled animation chains
- animations driving application logic
- inconsistent timing across components
- decorative animations without UX purpose
- blocking interactions during transitions